<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18460202-634">
               <interp inst="t18460202-634" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18460202"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18460202-634" type="date" value="18460202"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18460202-634-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-634-18460202 t18460202-634-offence-1 t18460202-634-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>634. <persName id="def1-634-18460202" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-634-18460202" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-634-18460202" type="age" value="17"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-634-18460202" type="surname" value="COLLINS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-634-18460202" type="given" value="JEREMIAH"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JEREMIAH COLLINS</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18460202-634-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18460202-634-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18460202-634-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="burglary"></interp> for burglariously breaking and entering the dwelling-house of <persName id="t18460202-name-926" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-926" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-926" type="surname" value="STACEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-926" type="given" value="PETER"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18460202-634-offence-1 t18460202-name-926"></join>Peter Stacey</persName>, about two in the night of the <rs id="t18460202-cd-27" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18460202-634-offence-1 t18460202-cd-27"></join>20th of Jan</rs>., and stealing therein 1 tea-caddy, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 1 box, 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 1/2lb. weight of tea, 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 1<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 1lb. weight of sugar, 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 1lb. weight of bacon, 8<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 4 sovereigns, 4 half-crowns, 25 shillings, and 10 sixpences, his property.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-927" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-927" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-927" type="surname" value="STACEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-927" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH STACEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at No. 40, Church-street, Rotherhithe. I am the wife of Peter Stacey—we keep a beer shop—on the 20th of Jan., on going down stairs at night I noticed a door closed which I usually left open—I put my hand against it, and felt something against it, some resistance, something outside, and on my shaking it the handle of a broom fell—on open<lb></lb>ing the door there is a window, as you come to the bottom of the stairs, which shows light into the bar—I saw the gas alight, and saw a man standing with his back against the window, with somethings lying on the table, he appeared to see me because he ran right to the door and escaped—I think the door must have been on the jar, closed, but not latched,—I did not hear him lift the latch—he had no shoes on—he had on a round jacket, and a cap, and cord trowsers—the gas was burning in the room—I missed four sovereigns and 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. worth of silver—I had left the money in a box, wrapped up in a piece of paper in a closet on the stairs overnight—some articles had been removed—a tea-caddy was taken off the mantle-piece with 1/2lb. of tea in it—I had seen the prisoner at our house the night before, but do not remember seeing him for several weeks before—I will not positively swear he is the man I saw in the parlour—but I have every reason to believe he is.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Other persons were fetched to your premises, were they not? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> When he ran to the door I called "Police"—a man crossed and asked what was the matter—I was frightened and did not tell him, but ran in doors and told my son and husband—I never heard of any<lb></lb>body else being taken—the prisoner did not give himself up, he was taken at the Eagle, just by my house—he came to my place, and said, "Does master want me?" I said, "I don't know, you had better call again," he went to the door and I had given information about him—I did not ask why he thought master wanted him—I thought he would run away if I questioned him—I could not detain him—I went immediately to the station—I was disturbed about a quarter past two o'clock in the night.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184602020170"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-928" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-928" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-928" type="surname" value="STACEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-928" type="given" value="PETER"></interp>PETER STACEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the witness's husband—I was the last person up—the house was quite secured—I went to bed at twenty minutes after eleven—I fastened the back doors—I went into the yard twice after I shut the front door—the street door was quite fastened—when the alarm was given I got up—my wife said something, when I came down—I went to the back door and found it shut, but the side part of the door jamb was broken away, a few boards taken out and a hole large enough for an arm to be put through and unbolt the door—I found a pair of shoes near the door, and outside the door a chisel, which I gave the policeman—my house is in the parish of Rotherhithe.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Is that the name of the parish? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I keep a beer and coffee shop.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-929" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-929" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-929" type="surname" value="LACK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-929" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES LACK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am toll-collector at the Thames Tunnel—about a quarter-past two on the morning of the robbery, I saw a man come out of the prosecutor's house, without shoes—he had on a short jacket and cap—he ran away—I had not an opportunity of seeing his features—I have known the prisoner several years—it is my firm belief he is the man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> This was the darkest time of the night, was it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, but there was a gas-light within eight or ten feet of the house, so I had an opportunity of seeing him—Mrs. Stacey was calling police the moment I came up to the door.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-930" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-930" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-930" type="surname" value="BRADLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-930" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM BRADLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Church-street, Rotherhithe, in the same house with the prisoner—I remember having some shoes from the prisoner's mother, to take to Cuddy's—I did not see them as they were in a hand<lb></lb>kerchief—I live in Mrs. Collins's house.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did not the prisoner come home at his usual hour that night? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, about half-past ten or eleven—he remained there all night, as far as I know—I saw him about nine o'clock next morning in his bed-room—he slept in the same room with his mother.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-931" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-931" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-931" type="surname" value="COLLINS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-931" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM COLLINS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a shoemaker, I know these shoes—I half-soled them for the prisoner, my work is on them—he brought them himself and fetched them away—I have reason to believe they are the shoes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You think there is some of your work on them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes (<hi rend="italic">pointing it out</hi>)—I can swear to the work—they are the shoes I have repaired twice for him—I know the soles, they are nailed, as he ordered them, as he walked and I knew his wear—I was a witness in the New Court twelve years ago, against a boy for robbing my master—I was never in custody—I did not see the prisoner after the robbery, till he was taken.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-932" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-932" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-932" type="surname" value="ANDREWS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-932" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL ANDREWS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable N</hi> 264.) I received these shoes from Stacey.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Had you notice of this robbery? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I knew nothing of it, till I heard a cry of "Police"—I went with Mr. Stacey to see if a certain boy was known at home.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-933" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-933" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-933" type="surname" value="HILL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-933" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD HILL</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi> 16.) I went to the Spread Eagle on Wednesday, the 21st of Jan., about half-past eleven, and found the prisoner in the tap-room—he denied the charge—I showed him the chisel—he said "It is mine," I told him to be careful what he said, as it would be used in evidence against him—and he then said, he knew nothing of the chisel.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How did you get the chisel? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I had it from Mr. Stacey—the prosecutor's is a well conducted house, for all I know—I did not hear that the prisoner was going to give himself up.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-934" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-934" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-934" type="surname" value="COLLINS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-934" type="given" value="JANE"></interp>JANE COLLINS</persName>
                  </hi>. I took the shoes home to the prisoner, after my husband had worked on them.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
